post_text:
We are pleased to inform you that Kingston will once again be participating in the Community Eligibility Program during the 2020-2021 school year. By participation in this program every child that is enrolled in our district will receive a healthy school breakfast and lunch at no charge each day. Your child(ren) will be able to participate in these meal programs without having to pay a fee or submit a meal application.
Please note that only full meals are reimbursable. If a child brings their lunch and only takes a milk the cost will be 30 cents. If your child wishes to purchase an extra milk with their tray the cost is 30 cents. If your child wishes to purchase any extras or a second tray they must have money in their meal account or pay cash.

post_text:
KINGSTON ADMINISTRATORS, TEACHERS, AND STAFF MEMBERS ARE AMAZING! YOUR STUDENTS ARE IN GOOD HANDS!
We're working very hard to be ready for whatever the new school year brings. Below is just one example of the technology training slides for "remote" learning that teachers have been working on the past two weeks. Every teacher in the Kingston K-14 School District is rewriting curriculum, devising lesson plans and teaching strategies for learners in the classroom, and for our remote learners. Our administrators are devising plans for the use of computer hardware and software for all of our students, and solving all of the other problems associated with Covid-19. Problem solving during this pandemic will be an ongoing process, virtually every day. As remote learning information, or virtual open house information becomes available, we will keep our Kingston Family informed. Every member of the district is working overtime to solve any problems that this challenging school year will throw our way. KINGSTON K-14 IS UP TO THE CHALLENGE!
WE APPRECIATE YOUR UNDERSTANDING!

KINGSTON GYMNASIUM FLOOR BEING REPAIRED AND UPDATED
Workers from Missouri Floor Company (Maryland Heights) began a three-week Kingston High School Gymnasium renovation, (Monday, August 10th). One quarter of the floor boards will be replaced on the west end, and the entire floor will be completely stripped and sanded. The floor will be refinished with brand new painted graphics and multiple topcoats. Kingston Gymnasium has not had a major resurfacing in 35 years.

PLEASE WELCOME OUR NEW FACILITIES DIRECTOR--
Kingston K-14 School District has hired Mr. Chris Clapp, as Facilities Director. Chris comes on board at a time when K-14 has extra maintenance requirements because of district growth, and extra cleaning and sanitizing responsibilities during this Covid-19 pandemic. He is a former Kingston K-14 student, and comes to the district from Farmington R-7, where he worked for six years.

IN-SCHOOL OR VIRTUAL SCHOOL SURVEY
HERE IS THE LINK: https://forms.gle/HZ2BBVnrmCFgqHyk9

As we prepare for the 2020-2021 school year, we would like to know if your child will be attending in-person instruction or virtual instruction. If you choose the virtual option, you may opt out after the 1st quarter if your child is in K-5, and you may opt out after the 1st semester if they are in grades 6-12. We realize that you might not have enough information to make the final decision right now, but we need a general idea of how many parents might choose each option in order to finalize our virtual and in-person staffing. Please fill out this survey letting us know what you are planning for each school-age child in your household.
THANK YOU FOR YOUR CONSIDERATION ABOUT THIS IMPORTANT TOPIC!

POTOSI VS. KINGSTON AT GENE LAWSON MEMORIAL FIELD
The Potosi Trojans earned a hard-fought win over our Kingston Cougars today, (Monday, July 13), 6-3. Potosi scored two insurance runs in the top of the seventh to secure the victory. Considering the lack of practice time leading up to this game, both teams pitched well and played good defense.
(Photo by Kingston Alumna Allison Fogelbach)

To be eligible for Pre-school, a student must be 3 years of age by July 31, 2020; and to be Kindergarten eligible, a student must be 5 years of age by July 31, 2020. To schedule a screening time, please call the Kingston Business Office at 573.438.4982 ext 880. Please bring a birth certificate, shot records, parent photo i.d., proof of residency, and custodial paperwork if necessary. Only one adult with child(ren) please.

post_text:
Grab n' go meals are today from 12:00-2:00.

To ensure the students in Washington County continue to receive healthy and nutritious meals during the summer, Kingston K-14 School District, will provide an opportunity for families to drive through and pick up grab n’go meals for the children 18 years and younger in front of the main building.
Meals will be served on Wednesdays from 12:00-2:00, until further notice.
While schools are closed, nutritionally balanced meals will be provided to all children 18 years and younger regardless of race, color, sex, disability, age, or national origin. Children are not required to be enrolled in Kingston K-14 School District to be eligible for service; even if your child is open enrolled in another district or has not yet started school you may still participate.

First State Community Bank (FSCB) Representative, Mrs. Bridgette Sansegraw, (right) presented Kingston Food Service Director, Mrs. Leta Lute, with a "Community Impact Program" check in the amount of $500 for the Kingston Closure Food Service Program. In a statement, FSCB Potosi Market President, Mr. Don Thompson, said, "We wanted to show our appreciation of your efforts to feed area children during this Covid-19 pandemic." THANK YOU, FIRST STATE COMMUNITY BANK!

If you have not taken the Summer Meal Survey we encourage you to do so today. This will help us know how much food to prepare for Wednesday.

Kingston K-14 Summer Drive-Through Meal Pick Up Survey
To help us with meal preparation please fill out this short survey. This form may be sent out in an email, please do not submit twice.
With the last official day of school on May 15, we will no longer be delivering meals. On Wednesday, May 20, we will begin our drive-through pick-up for meals here on campus for any child age 18 or younger and will continue until further notice. Each Wednesday, we will provide 5 days worth of meals. Food will be available for pick-up from 12:00-2:00 in front of the main building. We will not be sending out reminder messages for meal pick-up, so please set an alert on your phone to come down and pick-up the meals.
Please click the link below to fill out the form. Thank you
https://forms.gle/kZDk6uBJCcVGA3Sd8

post_text:
MATH WIZARDS!
Kingston Junior High School's Seventh and Eighth Grade Mathematics Team placed second at the 50th Annual Mineral Area Math Teachers Association Mathematics Competition, held on the campus of Mineral Area College, (Monday, March 9). More than 450 middle school (junior high) and high school students from 17 public, parochial, and home schools participated in the event. Kingston Junior High students, Seventh Grader Brynden Michalek (first place), and Eighth Grader Gabi Delapaz (second place), earned individual honors, leading their team to the second place finish. WE ARE VERY PROUD OF YOU!

post_text:
SAY SOMETHING!
Kingston K-14 Junior High and High School held a T-shirt fundraiser for the "Say Something" Foundation last week. SAY SOMETHING FOUNDATION is a nonprofit organization dedicated to suicide prevention through education. From the foundation's website: "People live everyday lives in a struggle. The struggle might be thoughts of suicide. It might be anxiety or depression. Or it could simply be a feeling of overwhelming helplessness. These people may need resources and/or receive services. SAY SOMETHING aims to help not just those afflicted with suicidal thoughts, but anyone who feels a struggle to get through life." IF YOU'RE STRUGGLING AND NEED HELP, PLEASE "SAY SOMETHING!" THE KINGSTON FAMILY CARES!
(Photo by KHS Sophomore McKenzy Martinez)

post_text:
PLEASE WELCOME OUR NEW SUPERINTENDENT!
Dr. Lee Ann Wallace, current Primary Principal in the Hillsboro R-3 School District, will become the new Kingston K-14 Superintendent of Schools, beginning July 1. Dr. Wallace’s hiring was finalized by the Kingston Board of Education on Tuesday, February 18. She will replace current Kingston Superintendent, Alex McCaul, who will become the superintendent of the Potosi R-3 District.
Dr. Wallace is a 28-year veteran of education. She is finishing her third year as a primary school principal at Hillsboro. Dr. Wallace spent 13 years in the Hayti R-II School District as a Building Administrator. She taught in the Portageville School District for 11 years.
Dr. Wallace has a Bachelor’s Degree from Arkansas State University (1992), A Master’s Degree in Educational Leadership and Administration from Southeast Missouri State University (2001), and her Doctor of Education (Ed.D.) in Educational Leadership and Administration from Saint Louis University (2015).
